<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1163,1440]" pageId="6" pageNumber="250">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1163,1188]" pageId="6" pageNumber="250">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the keys to the males of the British species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Disney, 1989" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="1989" box="[918,1211,1163,1188]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[918,1035,1163,1188]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="250">Megaselia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Disney" box="[1051,1203,1163,1188]" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle flies. Diptera, Phoridae, genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">
Disney, 
<number box="[1146,1203,1163,1187]" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
this species runs to couplet 
<number box="[240,285,1199,1223]" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" value="283.0">283</number>
, to 
<taxonomicName authority="Wood" authorityName="Wood" box="[324,529,1199,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maura">
<emphasis box="[324,434,1200,1223]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="250">M. maura</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
. It’s distinguished from the new species by having the fore metatarsus longer and narrower, and by the hypopygium, which has an epandrium with a different shape and with some stronger hairs. 
<taxonomicName authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wickerensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="250">M. wickerensis</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
, which run to couplet 
<quantity box="[616,687,1271,1296]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.239" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" unit="in" value="285.0">285 in</quantity>
the British key, has a very similar hypopygium to the new species, but it differs from the new species, by having the hairs on epandrium about as strong as those on cerci, as well as in the costal index, costal ratios and relative length of costal cilia and axillary bristles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney" box="[1091,1342,1343,1368]" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" refString="Disney, R. H. L. &amp; Perry, I. (2000) A new species of Megaselia from Cambridgeshire (Diptera, Phoridae). Dipterist Digest, 7, 5 - 7." type="journal article" year="2000">
Disney &amp; Perry, 
<number box="[1281,1342,1343,1367]" pageId="6" pageNumber="250" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
